<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-933-672  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 933 672.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 4 1989 v6 n48 p125(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PC executives expect tough 1990 amid market lag, buyer confusion.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burke, Steven; March, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Microcomputer executives who gathered at the Salomon BrothersDesktop Computing Conference predict flat revenues and a continuedslowdown in the microcomputer industry in 1990.andP;  The executivescite buyer anxiety over the future of the economy as well asunfulfilled promises of large productivity improvements fromproducts as key reasons for the gloomy outlook.andP;  Microcomputermanufacturers will have to put off expansion and concentrate oncost cutting to weather the slowdown.andP;  Some vendors and resellersare trying to increase revenue by achieving greater sales volume.andO;Another contributing factor to the flat forecast is hardwaremanufacturers' concentration on product development in the moreexpensive segment of the market.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ExecutiveForecastingComputer industryMicrocomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Recent PC sales trail year-ago levels. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>PC Executives Expect Tough 1990 Amid Market Lag, Buyer ConfusionandM;NEW YORK--PC executives last week warned that industry revenues may be flatnext year, due to buyer confusion and anxiety over a possible recession.andM;&quot;It's going to be a tough year in 1990,&quot; said Jack Browne Jr., director ofmarketing at Motorola Inc., in Schaumburg, Ill.andP;  &quot;Most people have a verycautious outlook.&quot;andM;Browne was one of many industry executives who shared a somber view of theindustry as they attended the Salomon Brothers Desktop Computing Conferencehere last week.andM;Forecasting flat revenue growth in the PC industry in 1990, Browne blamed theslowdown on the general economy.andP;  He said large-volume PC customers withlimited capital won't be willing to replace existing technology.andM;Industry executives also cited the unfulfilled promise of dramaticimprovement to productivity from new PC products.andM;&quot;People are beginning to question the millions of dollars spent on PCs,&quot; saidJames Heisch, senior vice president of reseller Businessland Inc. in SanJose, Calif.andP;  Heisch said industry growth, which averaged 30 percent to 40percent in the last several years, will slow to 10 percent to 15 percent forthe fourth quarter of 1989 and all of next year.andP;  He predicted moreconsolidation in the retail channel.andM;While executives gave widely differing figures for past and future growth,they agreed that the current slowdown has forced many companies to tightentheir belts and postpone expansion.andP;  The slowdown also has parked a wave ofdiscounting as vendors and resellers attempt to increase revenue by pushinggreater sales volume.andM;&quot;I see an awful lot of discounting in the U.S.andP;  and Europe,&quot; said John Roach,chairman of Tandy Corp. in Fort Worth, Texas.andP;  He said that indicates somecompanies are not selling as much as they expected.andM;&quot;It's a turbulent market right now,&quot; said Gordon Campbell, president of Chipsandamp; Technologies Inc. in San Jose, Calif.andP;  &quot;It's not nearly as comfortable asit used to be.&quot;andM;Campbell said the PC industry grew at a 20 percent clip last year, but addedthat it will only grow 10 percent in units and 5 percent in revenue nextyear.andP;  Asked the reasons for the slowdown, Campbell said, &quot;I wish I knew.&quot;andM;PC firms may have had unrealistic expectations of high growth, Campbell said.andO;&quot;We have been in a go-go environment of 30 percent plus growth for the lastseveral years.andP;  This [present situation] is probably a normal businessenvironment.&quot;andM;Even so, David Carnevale, an analyst with market-researcher InfoCorp in SantaClara, Calif., is concerned that domestic PC sales have been below 1988levels for three straight months.andP;  Unit sales through domestic dealers inOctober, for instance, slipped to 221,000 units, down from 248,000 in thesame month a year ago.andM;Fear of a recession and the anticipation of new hardware and software are twofactors that Carnevale said contribute to slower sales.andP;  But perhaps moreimportant, he continued, hardware manufacturers are concentrating theirdevelopment of new products ont he more expensive segment of the market.andM;IBM's PC business is not feeling the pinch, said James Cannavino, vicepresident of IBM's Personal Systems Group in White Plains, N.Y.andP;  IBM's salesin October and November were stronger than in those months last year, and thecompany's PC business grew faster than the industry in the third quarter ofthis year, he said.andM;Donald Casey, vice president of Apple Computer Inc., in Cupertino, Calif.,andO;said 1989 has not been an easy year for the industry.andP;  &quot;Growth began to slow,and many companies began to transition their product lines,&quot; he said, adding,however, that Apple has continued to thrive.andO;</TEXT></DOC>